diff:1613102924:1613102924:=1,40d0%0a%3c :Category: PracticeCategory%0a%3c :Expansion: Practice Practice Practice%0a%3c :Author: TimG%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.VarietyOfSounds|VarietyOfSounds]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.saumyaB|saumyaB]]%0a%3c :Section: %0a%3c :Completed: 11.02.2021 - 20:08%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I think that pronouncing sounds has everything to do with practice. By virtue of the fact that every sound in the IPA chart corresponds to a sound in at least one language (which means that at least one person can pronounce that sound "fluently"), it is possible for humans to produce every sound fluently. However, no language has all of the IPA sounds in it, this much is obvious.%0a%3c %0a%3c When learning your native language(s), as Professor Bjorndahl puts it, you spend a long time in the babbling phase, and it takes years for you to be able to produce all of your sounds naturally and be fluent. These years are practice time where you focus on virtually nothing else except learning how to speak. They also give you the framework for how your tongue should move in your mouth. Thus, when you try to make another sound, you not only don't have years of practice doing it, but it goes against the years of practice you have not doing that. Thus, I think that in order to learn every sound, you would have to practice for years at least. However, in theory (at least the theory I understand), there is no reason why one person wouldn't be able to make every sound.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
